    Dr. Faizan will inform you about the test 3 details.

    One more test on the syllabus of test 1 and test 2 will be conducted as a make up for test 1 and test 2. As the next two weeks are going to be very busy with the tests and submission of other subjects as well as comprehensive examinations of the previous semester, I am planning to conduct the make up test on 14 /11/2020.

    Best 2 out of test1, test 2 and makeup will be considered.

    Please give the suggestions.

    Best Wishes
    Sachin

    Dear Students,
    The correct answer for this question is 12.49 N-m which was not there in the option and hence correct answer was none of the above.

    What is the torque (approx) to be produced in a circular aluminum shaft (μ = 0.32) of length 1.8 m and radius 10 mm to produce a rate of twist of 0.03183 radians/m. Assume E = 66 GPa

11481002396_ME F217 » Forums » Announcements » Reg. Test 3
Picture of A R Harikrishnan . 	
Reg. Test 3
by A R Harikrishnan . - Monday, 16 November 2020, 6:48 PM
  	

Dear Students,

Kindly note the following regarding Test 3, which will be conducted on Canvas on Wednesday, 18th November 2020 during class hours.

    The syllabus includes Psychrometry+ VARS+ Gas Refrigeration.
    You are supposed to print and keep 2-3 copies (hardcopy) of Psychrometric chart so that you will be able to solve the problems related to psychrometry and air conditioning. 
    There is no negative marking.
    You are supposed to use only the thermodynamic tables from Thermodynamics: An Engineering Approach, Cengel and Boles (prescribed text book, 8th edition).
    Keep your calculators and prescribed thermodynamic tables with you.
    Carefully read any specific instructions given in each question.
    For any problems, Dr. Harikrishnan will be available in the class (link below) https://meet.google.com/kqu-awpm-gpz
    There will be a common data based problem problem. All the required figures will be available as a pdf file on Nalanda/Canvas at 4:00 pm on the test date. Please download that file before starting the test. The total test duration is 33 minutes. The questions will be a combination of numerical and MCQs. Test will start at 4.02 PM and will end at 4.35 PM.

Best wishes,

Harikrishnan

Dear Shyam Sunder,

One of your student has submitted the feedback for your course.The details are as follows:

Course No:  ME F212

Course Title:  FLUID MECHANICS

Feedback:  This feedback is with relation to the fluid mechanics test 3 conducted on 17/ 11/ 2020 Giving a single question based solely on limited concepts and expecting us to solve complex mathematical equations rather than actually conceptually solve problems. After studying throughout the night, trying to grasp every concept, he gives a single question with a seemingly sole purpose to fail us considering not much solving has been done during class or tutorial hours. And to add to our turmoil, a question in a particular set had a solution present on the internet which was easily found by the students and copied to be awarded full marks whereas people like me struggled to solve the question without considering the use of internet. Moreover, he changed the platform for the test last minute with no warning of any sort and we had to figure out what to do which ate up into the already limited time received to solve the quiz.

You can also view your course feedback on AUGSD/AGSRD website.

Dear All

There are two announcements:

1) Some of you mentioned that you have around three different evaluative components from other subjects this weekend.

Therefore, let us have the Objective Quiz 4 on 25th November 2020 (Wednesday) during tutorial hour (8:00 AM). 

Syllabus: Dimensional analysis and Similarity + Viscous flow in ducts (Pipe flow)

2) Some of you have missed Test 1 or Test 2 or Test 3 due to reasons attributed to Covid 19.  A makeup test will be held on the class before the last working day, i.e., on 28th November 2020 (Saturday) during Lecture hour (10:00 AM).

Syllabus for makeup: It will not be possible to give separate syllabus according to the test you missed. A common syllabus will be decided soon.

I will send separate emails to those who have missed the tests.

3) No makeup will be provided for Objective Quiz.

Please prepare accordingly and do not ask for any further rescheduling.

Best wishes for the comprehensive exams.

Thanks.




-- 
Dr. Shyam Sunder Yadav
Assistant Professor
Mechanical Engineering
BITS Pilani

Subject: 11481001170_GS F232: IP T 3 Answer Key
From: "Tanu Shukla . (via Nalanda)" <noreply-nalanda1@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 23-11-2020, 19:32
To: "ASWIN BENEDICT ." <f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Reply-to: "Do not reply to this email"

11481001170_GS F232 » Forums » Announcements » IP T 3 Answer Key
Picture of Tanu Shukla . 	
IP T 3 Answer Key
by Tanu Shukla . - Monday, 23 November 2020, 6:40 PM
  	

I.                     Correct sequence (5*2 = 10)

 1.      Arrange the following in the order of their occurrence:

Chunking, sensory register, consolidation, elaborative rehearsal, selective attention

 i)               __________

ii)              __________

iii)            __________

iv)             __________

v)              __________

Ans: Sensory register, Selective attention, chunking, elaborative rehearsal, consolidation

 

2.  The correct sequence of motivational events is:

Drive reduction, Need, Drive, Goal achievement, Goal-directed behaviour

___________________________________________

Ans) Need, Drive, Goal-directed behaviour, Goal achievement, Drive reduction

II.             Mention True or False: (5*2=10)

a)     Information reaching the meaning level of processing and elaboration has the best chance of being retained (True)

b)     According to information processing theories of memory, information is transferred from stage to stage until some of it is finally lodged in long-term memory (True)

c)     A specific state within the organism that may elicit behaviour appropriate to the need often as a result of a disturbance in homeostasis is known as a drive. (True)

d)     Working memory is like a workbench where the material is constantly being handled, combined and transformed (True)

e)     Information maintained in the rehearsal buffer is prevented from decaying in STM (True)

III.           Fill in the blanks (12*2=24)

a)     Short term memory holds information for _________ seconds or less (30 s)

b)     A subject is presented four non-sense syllabus one by one each for two seconds. After the presentation of the four items, the subject is asked to count backwards aloud by threes from some number for fifteen seconds and after that he/she is asked to recall the non-sense syllabus. What memory storage is being measured in this experiment? ________ (Short term memory storage)

c)     Needs cause a psychological state or feeling called as _________ (Drive)

d)     Entry of information in long term memory depends on ____________ and __________ (Elaborative rehersal and Primary memory)

e)     Memory that contains factual information is called ____________ (Declarative memory/Semantic Memory) (0.5 – Explicit memory)

f)      Skills that are operated automatically and without thinking are rooted in _______ memory (Implicit memory/Procedural)

g)     Memory for surprising and consequential events (emotional public events) are known as __________ (Flash bulb memory) (0.5 – Episodic memory)

h)     When previous learning interferes with our memory of later learning it is referred to as ________ (proactive interference)

i)      Drive theories of motivation are also known as _____________ (Push theories of motivation)

j)      ___________ theory takes hedonistic view of motivation. (Opponent-process theory)

k)     A condition of drive is brought about in an organism whenever there is ____________ (disturbance/deprivation/need)

IV.            MCQs (7*2=14)

       i.         Working memory involves which of the following?

a.      Storage capacity and Biographical information

b.      Semantic information and Processing capacity

c.      Storage capacity and Processing capacity

d.      Biographical information and Semantic information

     ii.         Which of the following best describes the serial position curve?

a.      Greater accuracy of recall of words in the beginning of the list and in the middle of the list.

b.      Greater accuracy of recall of words in the beginning of the list and gradual diminished accuracy by the end of the list.

c.      Greater accuracy of recall of words in beginning and at end of the list.

d.      Greater accuracy of recall of words in the middle and at the end of the list.

    iii.          According to interference theory, which one of the following causes forgetting?

a.      Failure of storage

b.      Failure of encoding

c.      Failure of retrieval

d.      Response Competition

    iv.  Which of the following can be viewed as a homeostatic mechanism?

a)     hunger

b)     Thirst

c)     Sex

d)     Both a and b

      v.         Which of the following statements is not correct about drives?

a.      Drives beside being stimulated by biological factors, may also be induced by intense internal/external stimuli

b.      In addition to primary drives, we also have many secondary drives

c.      Neutral stimuli paired with strong drives can acquire motivating properties

d.     Primary drives depend on learning

 

    vi.         Fear is an example of

a.      acquired drive

b.      Aversive state of the organism aroused by stimuli that signal a future threatening event

c.      Example of instinct

d.     Both a and b

   vii.         Intrinsic motivation is closely related to the ________ of Maslow’s hierarchy.

a.      Lower levels

b.      Middle Levels

c.      Higher levels

V.             Explain (2 marks)

Episodic buffer refers to _____________________________________

(a component of working memory, is used to integrate and to store briefly the information from phonological loop and visuospatial sketch-pad)

See this post in context
Change your forum digest preferences

Subject: 11481001170_GS F232: IP T4 Answer Key
From: "Tanu Shukla . (via Nalanda)" <noreply-nalanda1@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 23-11-2020, 19:32
To: "ASWIN BENEDICT ." <f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Reply-to: "Do not reply to this email"

11481001170_GS F232 » Forums » Announcements » IP T4 Answer Key
Picture of Tanu Shukla . 	
IP T4 Answer Key
by Tanu Shukla . - Monday, 23 November 2020, 6:43 PM
  	

1. In classical conditioning when a strong CS is paired with a neutral stimulus causing the neutral stimulus to become a second CS is called

a.  Higher Order Conditioning

b. Stimulus Substitution

c.  Vicarious Conditioning

d. Discrimination Learning

2. After several visits to the doctor for chemotherapy, Anita finds that she begins to feel nauseous just sitting in the waiting room. According to classical conditioning, Anita’s feeling of nausea in the absence of chemotherapy is

a.  an unconditioned stimulus

b. an unconditioned response

c. a conditioned stimulus

d.  a conditioned response

3. A parent deliberately ignores a child’s temper tantrums in an attempt to discourage them. The parent’s strategy is in accordance with

 a. Negative reinforcement

b.  Extinction

c.  Operant escape

d. Operant avoidance

4.  Choose the correct behavioural outcomes from the options provided for the procedure mentioned.

Options:

i.                Learn to perform responses that produce pleasant outcome

ii.              Learn to suppress responses that lead to unpleasant outcome.

iii.             Learn to supress responses that lead to loss or postponement of desired stimulus

iv.             Learn to perform responses that permit to avoid or escape an unpleasant event.

a)     Positive reinforcement:  __________________

b)     Negative reinforcement: __________________

c)     Positive Punishment: _____________________

d)     Negative Punishment: ____________________

Ans: 1 4 2 3

5. Which of the following is not a characteristic feature of Tolman’s theory of learning?

a.  Purposive Behaviour

b. Vicarious trial and error

c. Contiguity

d. Latent learning

6. Mention whether the following belong to the mechanism of operant learning?

a) Events that follow an action (Yes/No) ______ Yes

b) Involuntary response (Yes/No) ______  No

c) Processes that weakens or suppresses behaviour (Yes/No) _______ Yes

d) Use of consequences to strengthen behaviour (Yes/No) _____ Yes

7. True or False (8x1= 8 marks)

a)       Classical conditioning is quick when UCS is presented immediately after CS rather than before. (TRUE)

b)       Organisms learn to suppress responses that lead to removal of pleasant consequences. (TRUE)

c)       Punishment weakens responses that precede occurrence of stimulus. (TRUE)

d)       It is possible for learning to remain dormant for a considerable length of time before it is manifested in behaviour (TRUE)

e)       Reinforcement is not important for latent learning (False)

f)        Latent learning is not translated into performance (True)

g)       According to Bandura, the behaviour is fully determined by mental images of past experiences (False)

h)       Information gained from observations is stored symbolically in retentional processes to make it useful (True)

 

8. Which of the following are the correct explanations of discrimination and stimulus generalizations?  (Yes/No)

(a) Learning to respond to one stimulus but not to the other similar stimuli. ________

 (b) Learning to respond to one stimulus but not to the other different stimuli.  ______

(c) Stimuli similar to the one used during conditioning also elicit the conditioned response.  _____

(d) Stimuli different to the one used during conditioning also elicit the conditioned response. ____

 Ans: (a) and (c) – Yes; (b) and (d) - No

9. Assertion (A): Learning refers to the modification of behavior as a result of past experience. Reason (R): Experience is achieved through observation.

a. Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of (A).

 b. A and R are correct, but R is not the correct explanation of (A).

 c. A is true, but R is false.

d. R is true, but A is false.

 

10. A person rattles the box of dog's biscuits before giving the biscuit to dog. As the person rattles the box the dog begins to salivate. Thus, rattling of box is _____; and the salivation of dog is a kind of _______.

Ans:  CS; CR

11. Name the Psychologist who proposed the following phenomenon

a)     Observational learning _________

b)     Cognitive Maps _______

c)     Association of different stimuli ________

Ans) Bandura, Tolman, Pavlov

 

See this post in context
Change your forum digest preferences

    Dear All

    There are two announcements:

    1) Some of you mentioned that you have around three different evaluative components from other subjects this weekend.

    Therefore, let us have the Objective Quiz 4 on 25th November 2020 (Wednesday) during tutorial hour (8:00 AM). 

    Syllabus: Dimensional analysis and Similarity + Viscous flow in ducts (Pipe flow)

    2) Some of you have missed Test 1 or Test 2 or Test 3 due to reasons attributed to Covid 19.  A makeup test will be held on the class before the last working day, i.e., on 28th November 2020 (Saturday) during Lecture hour (10:00 AM).

    I will send separate emails to those who have missed the tests.

    3) No makeup will be provided for Objective Quiz.

    Please prepare accordingly and do not ask for any further rescheduling.

Comprehensive Examination
by Tanu Shukla . - Tuesday, 8 December 2020, 7:54 PM
  	


Comprehensive examination of GSF 232 Introductory Psychology Date: 14th December 2020, FN (10 AM - 12 Noon). 


Join the class using the google meet link: https://meet.google.com/jtc-octv-qce

The syllabus for the test has already been shared in the previous posts. 

It will be a closed book test. 

Objective and descriptive type questions would be asked. 

The test would be assigned on google classroom at the scheduled time.

Announcement
	
I have just discussed the modus operandi for our upcoming end-semester evaluation on 15th December, 2020. I would be posting the questions in an MS word document here in this google class room. You can download the document, write down your name and ID number and start answering them. I would open the google document at 11:30 am; at that point of time you can copy/paste the answers from the MS word document and submit the google form. You are required to use the google form to submit your final answers. I will be in the google meet (regular class link) for the first 15 mins and the last 30 mins to clarify any doubts.

Syllabus: The four movies done in class and the novel, Siddhartha.

Good Luck!

Dear All, 
Please check your marks on Nalanda in the next one hour. some points are given below.
Regarding Section 1 of the comprehensive exam.
1. It is possible that the students may see the score on aws.nalanda more than the one shown on Dashboard (bits-pilani.ac.in) This because of the negative marking scheme for section 1. Please go through the test properly and then only write back to me if you have any query.
2.There are around 23 students who never submitted the test. Fortunately I could extract their submission from Nalanda and manually done their evaluations hence these students may not be able to see the evaluation on Nalanda.
3. Answer sheets submitted in google drive as well as on Nalanda are evaluated. Those who submitted on Nalanda can see the answer sheet there only. You may be able to see some remarks also with the answer sheet.
4.Answer sheets submitted through email are not evaluated as it was announced well in advance to upload the answer sheets on Nalanda only and form Dummy test was also provided, unfortunately very few students attempted the dummy test.  However, I have checked the answer sheets uploaded on google drive also.
5. Post comprehensive average is 136.88 and comprehensive average is 18.51.
6. If there is any genuine doubt then only write to me.
7. It is difficult for me to share the answer sheets summitted on google drive.
8. Soon you will be able to see the answers on aws.Nalanda
9. Uploading of the marks is in progress wait.

Thanking you

Subject: Tentative Timetable for Second Semester 2020-21
From: Time Table <timetable@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 05-01-2021, 18:21
To: students@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in
CC: Associate Dean AUGSD <ad.augsd@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, Associate Dean AGSRD Pilani <ad.agsrd@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>

Dear All,

 

Please find attached the latest tentative Timetable for Second Semester 2020-21. This timetable includes the courses for the ongoing students (second semester starting from 16th Jan) as well as for the newly admitted students (second semester starting from 10th March), accordingly courses have comprehensive exam dates either in May or June respectively.

 

You are requested to submit a timetable related query (if any) under "Query Submission" through AUGS-AGSR website (https://academic.bits-pilani.ac.in)  latest by  12 noon, 7th Jan. 2020, in case of any discrepancy in CDC Courses and required number of Elective Courses.


Please note that we will try our best to resolve your queries  and the revised tentative timetable will again be shared on 10th Jan 2021. 

Please wait for the revised timetable and do not drop multiple queries and emails.


You are also advised not to reply back to this email. All requests must come through the query form as suggested above. Queries sent via email will not be entertained.

 

  

Timetable Team

Subject: 11491002430_ME F220: Three dimensional steady state heat conduction
From: "P Srinivasan . (via Nalanda)" <psrinivasan@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 19-01-2021, 11:45
To: "ASWIN BENEDICT ." <f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Reply-to: "P Srinivasan ."

11491002430_ME F220 » Forums » Announcements » Three dimensional steady state heat conduction
Picture of P Srinivasan . 	
Three dimensional steady state heat conduction
by P Srinivasan . - Tuesday, 19 January 2021, 11:13 AM
  	

Dear Students,

As discussed in the class, i am providing the two papers related to the general heat conduction equation.Please refer the same. (You need not understand the paper completely). You can see the governing equation and the temperature distribution in the billet.

Links for the papers are given they are easily downloadable.

https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1290072914001380

https://asmedigitalcollection.asme.org/HT/proceedings-abstract/HT2012/44786/963/245223


I hope you enjoy learning heat transfer with practical applications.

best wishes

P Srinivasan

Dear Students,

    All the tutorial tests for all sections shall be conducted through the course page on CANVAS. 
    An invitation to join the page has already been sent to you. Check your email inbox.
    If you have not received an invitation or you are facing any issue in joining the course page, share your details by replying to this email.
    You must join the page before the first tutorial class on Monday (Jan 25, 2021).
    Tutorial tests will be posted as assignments on the page.
    Links to recorded videos of tutorials will also be posted regularly on the same page.
    You shall submit your solutions as a single scanned pdf file before the due time for every tutorial test.
    Email submissions will not be accepted.
    Rechecking requests if any shall be submitted by writing a private comment under the marks assigned to you.
    You may also install the CANVAS STUDENT mobile app for students on your mobile device for easy access.

 

-- 
Regards,
Gaurav Watts,
Assistant Professor,
Department of Mechanical Engineering,

PoE: No Class Tomorrow (29th Jan 2021)
by Rahul Arora . - Thursday, 28 January 2021, 7:40 PM
  	

Dear Students,

There will be no regular class tomorrow. The compensatory lecture will be taken next week. The date and time for the compensatory lecture will be communicated well in advance. 

On a related note, the slides and the lecture recordings are uploading on Nalanda, please visit the Nalanda page regularly. More slides will be uploaded once the module will complete.

Keep learning.

best wishes

Dear Students,

Those who have not yet accepted the Canvas invite, please accept as soon as possible, otherwise, you will miss this component. 

Following are the final instructions for attempting tomorrow's tut test at 8 AM.

1. Log into your Canvas account and click on the course. This you can do even before 8 AM. Check your time settings by clicking on the tab Settings on your lefthand side. If not set at New Delhi (+5:30) then set it first.

2. Join the respective tutorial class link with your Video ON and Audio ON throughout the test. This will be noted by the invigilators and by the google system.

3. Put your headphones jack in the port so that any voice could not disturb you (don't wear the headphones). In case you want to ask anything, please write to the chatbox. Keep checking the chatbox after every 10 minutes for any announcement.

4. On the Canvas course page, Go to the Quizzes tab showing on your left-hand side in blue color. You will see the Practice Quizzes tab under which you will see the option ID and Name Check which will not be available until 8:05 AM.

5. At 8:05 AM, click on the ID and Name Check and start attempting it. This contains two questions. You need to answer it and submit it within 3 (three) minutes. You need to write your name and ID on the given space.

6. After submission, go back to the Quizzes tab. Within three minutes, a new tab Assignment Quizzes will be visible to you (if not then click on the Quizzes tab again to refresh). Click on the Tut Test 1- 9th Feb 2021 to start the test.

7. Once started, you will be given 30 (thirty) minutes to attempt the 30 (thirty) questions. Each carry one mark. 

8. As per the instructions shared yesterday, one question at a time will be visible. After choosing the correct option, click on the next for the next question. Remember the questions are locked, you cannot go back and change your answer. Also, you cannot leave a question blank by thinking that you will come later and attempt. This is not allowed, therefore optimize your time accordingly.

9. After attempting all the questions you need to click on Submit option. If you do not submit within 30 minutes then it will automatically be submitted and close. Your answers will remain saved within the system. Don't worry. 

10. The exam is an open book exam and all questions are self-explanatory. Please don't ask any doubt. Whatever you interpret, choose the best option.

11. There is No Negative Marking.

12. Join your respective Tutorial section - Those who have mistakenly assigned T1 can join the link given against T17. The changes are notified to the authorities and will be done soon.

    T2 Mr. Aman Takiyar -  meet.google.com/hdo-driq-aba
    T3 Ms. Pratibha Saini -  meet.google.com/nac-jqcs-uxp
    T4 Ms. Neha Jain - meet.google.com/nkz-pntf-wvu
    T5 Ms. Anuradha Singh - meet.google.com/pus-qgku-wid

Dear Students,

The two students have not yet accepted the Canvas invite, please accept as soon as possible before the test, otherwise, you will miss this component also. 

Following are the final instructions for attempting tomorrow's tut test at 8 AM.

1. Log into your Canvas account and click on the course. This you can do even before 8 AM. Check your time settings by clicking on the tab Settings on your lefthand side. If not set at New Delhi (+5:30) then set it first. If you have already done the same before tut-test 1 then ignore this step.

2. Join the respective tutorial class link with your Video ON and Audio ON throughout the test. This will be noted by the invigilators and by the google system.

3. Put your headphones jack in the port so that any voice could not disturb you (don't wear the headphones). In case you want to ask anything, please write to the chatbox. Keep checking the chatbox after every 10 minutes for any announcement.

4. On the Canvas course page, Go to the Quizzes tab showing on your left-hand side in blue color. 

5. At 8:05 AM, click on the Tut Test 2 - 23rd Feb 2021 to start the test.

6. Once started, you will be given 30 (thirty) minutes to attempt the 30 (thirty) questions. Each carries one mark. 

7. The quiz instructions remain the same. One question at a time will be visible. After choosing the correct option, click on the next for the next question. Remember the questions are locked, you cannot go back and change your answer. Also, you cannot leave a question blank by thinking that you will come later and attempt. This is not allowed, therefore optimize your time accordingly.

8. After attempting all the questions you need to click on Submit option. If you do not submit within 30 minutes then it will automatically be submitted and close. Your answers will remain saved within the system. Don't worry. 

9. The exam is an open book exam and all questions are self-explanatory. Please don't ask any doubt. Whatever you interpret, choose the best option.

10. There is No Negative Marking.

11. Join your respective Tutorial section - Those who have mistakenly assigned T1 and still not sure about their tutorial section can join the link given against T17.

Subject: 11491002399_ME F221_MF F221: Mid Sem Exam related instructions
From: "Jitendra Singh Rathore . (via Nalanda)" <jitendrarathore@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 02-03-2021, 11:32
To: "ASWIN BENEDICT ." <f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Reply-to: "Jitendra Singh Rathore ."

11491002399_ME F221_MF F221 » Forums » Announcements » Mid Sem Exam related instructions
Picture of Jitendra Singh Rathore . 	
Mid Sem Exam related instructions
by Jitendra Singh Rathore . - Tuesday, 2 March 2021, 11:00 AM
  	

Instructions to Students

1.            Mid Sem Exam is open book type. Only class notes, Text book’s PDF and AUTOCAD are allowed.

2.            Join the Mercer Mettl platform before 1:45 PM. The test will begin at 1:55 PM.

3.            You can access test link only until 2:10 PM. If a student will not join Mettl within the time window, he or she will be marked absent in Mid Sem Exam.

4.            The exam duration is 90 minutes. Extra 15 minutes are kept for file uploading.

5.            Exam will be closed by Instructor In-charge sharp at 3:45 PM. No submission after 3:45 PM irrespective of time remaining on your mercer platform OR any power failure/internet failure.

6.            Write your answers on plain papers. Write your ID number, name and put the signature on each page.

7.            Question related to Velocity and acceleration analysis: Graphical approach need to be solved in AUTOCAD and convert the AUTOCAD file as a PDF and upload at proper place.

 

Best wishes

Dear students,

Note the following regardingMechanisms and Machines mid sem exam

1.            Mid Sem Exam is open book type. Only class notes, Text book’s PDF and AUTOCAD are allowed.

2.            Join the Mercer Mettl platform before 1:45 PM. The test will begin at 1:55 PM.

3.            You can access test link only until 2:10 PM. If a student will not join Mettl within the time window, he or she will be marked absent in Mid Sem Exam. No make up.

4.            The exam duration is 90 minutes. Extra 15 minutes are kept for file uploading.

5.            Exam will be closed by Instructor In-charge sharp at 3:45 PM. No submission after 3:45 PM irrespective of time remaining on your mercer platform OR any power failure/internet failure.

6.            Write your answers on plain papers. Write your ID number, name and put the signature on each page.

7.            Question related to Velocity and acceleration analysis: Graphical approach needs to be solved in AUTOCAD and convert the AUTOCAD file as a PDF and upload at the proper place.

 

Best wishes


Dr J S Rathore

Dear students,

Note a few more points along with correction to point 7 in the previous email.

 

No Matlab/Python/excel OR any such tools for calculation purpose.


Corrections for the point 7 mentioned in previous email: 

§  Instead of converting AUTOCAD files to PDF files, you have to submit the snippets of velocity and acceleration diagrams for the Graphical Analysis question. For reference, you can view the solution of the First tutorial test uploaded on Nalanda AWS.

§  Tabulate the velocity and acceleration answers on paper, and submit them through the QR Code Scanner option.

§  Mention as many dimensions as possible. No clarifications/requests regarding the same will be accepted once the examination ends.


best wishes


On Tue, Mar 2, 2021 at 11:32 AM Jitendra S. Rathore <jitendrarathore@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in> wrote:

    Dear students,

    Note the following regardingMechanisms and Machines mid sem exam

    1.            Mid Sem Exam is open book type. Only class notes, Text book’s PDF and AUTOCAD are allowed.

    2.            Join the Mercer Mettl platform before 1:45 PM. The test will begin at 1:55 PM.

    3.            You can access test link only until 2:10 PM. If a student will not join Mettl within the time window, he or she will be marked absent in Mid Sem Exam. No make up.

    4.            The exam duration is 90 minutes. Extra 15 minutes are kept for file uploading.

    5.            Exam will be closed by Instructor In-charge sharp at 3:45 PM. No submission after 3:45 PM irrespective of time remaining on your mercer platform OR any power failure/internet failure.

    6.            Write your answers on plain papers. Write your ID number, name and put the signature on each page.

    7.            Question related to Velocity and acceleration analysis: Graphical approach needs to be solved in AUTOCAD and convert the AUTOCAD file as a PDF and upload at the proper place.

     

    Best wishes

Subject: 11491001023_ECON F211: ECON F211: Mid-Sem Final Instructions
From: "Rahul Arora . (via Nalanda)" <rahul.arora@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>

11491001023_ECON F211 » Forums » Announcements » ECON F211: Mid-Sem Final Instructions
Picture of Rahul Arora . 	
ECON F211: Mid-Sem Final Instructions
by Rahul Arora . - Thursday, 4 March 2021, 10:03 PM
  	

Dear Students,

Following are the final instructions for tomorrow's (5th Mar 2021) mid-sem exam scheduled at 11 AM:

Related to Question paper: 

    All the questions are compulsory
    The question paper is divided into three sections: Part A, Part B, and Part C.
    Sections sequencing is fixed so you need to attempt each section one by one and one after the other in a set sequence. You cannot skip any section, however, you can leave the questions unanswered. 
    You will get 105 minutes in total to complete the exam and upload.
    The first section (Part A) is timed and you need to complete all the questions in Part A within the first 40 minutes. The type of questions and their weightage will get to know at the time of the exam. Please do not ask through separate emails. 
    The remaining time is for Part B and Part C consisting of two questions in each part. The suggestion is to allocate the remaining time equally to both sections carrying equal weightage where you need to upload your answers while writing their explanation on the space provided.
    In Part B and Part C there are two questions, each. Read the below instructions carefully for attempting the questions in Part B and Part C: 
    Part B and Part C contain the problem-solving type questions. Solve the questions using pen and paper, including all steps and calculations and scan and upload the image for each question using the QR code. This is important for section 2 and section 3: In addition to solving the question on a piece of paper and uploading it, also type how you have solved the question (mention very brief, to the point steps in the space provided) and also type the final answer value. Please note that uploading the answer is also mandatory. We have set the time limit in such a way that you will be able to solve the question, scan and upload it, and also type the brief steps and final solution. Please ensure that you follow these instructions.

    Do not forget to write your Name, ID number, course number, and date on each page of your answer sheet. To get the full score, you need to show all the steps required to arrive at the final answer with proper interpretation.
    All questions are self-explanatory, so write your answer as per your understanding of the question as per the class discussion.
    Online browsing will not be tolerated. If any student will be found with the browsing, her/his paper will not be evaluated. Remember, we are also looking at your screen.
    Don't send your answer sheets to my email during or after the exam. It will not be considered. Please do not ask for this. This is as per the AUGSD guidelines. 
    The Mid-Sem test is Open Book and you can access any study material, provided they are not surfing the internet.
    This evaluative component is proctored so read the Mettl instructions carefully and be alert because you will be watched each time by the invigilators. Please concentrate on your exam only and cooperate with the proctor.

Related to Attempt in Mettl:

    Please adhere to the guidelines of AUGSD & Timetable related to the Mercer Mettl Platform. Please be ready with all the necessary technology specified by the AUGSD/Timetable for giving an exam on the Mettl platform.
    Be alert and join as per the instructions given while your training on Mettl.
    You will receive a link in your email by 10:50 AM and you can start the exam after 10:55 AM. To start the exam, you need to click on the link and after inserting an OTP (received on your email) your exam will start. The clock counting 105 minutes will start. A separate clock counting 40 minutes for part A will also be displayed. Also, remember that the exam link will remain active for few minutes only so requesting you all to join on time.
    Please ensure no disturbances during the exam time. Please ensure the highest ethics and maintain the decorum of the exam.

Additional Instruction from my Experience with Mettl:

    For those who are not able to join, wait for some time and try after a minute. Don't worry, your time will start once you enter into the exam window.
    For those who are not able to receive the OTP wait for some time, refresh your email inbox, and get it.
    Still, after few minutes you are not getting OTP then click on the link again for getting a new OTP. Do all those things patiently. 
    You can also get 504 error for which wait for some time to connect or again join using the link and new OTP.
    If you disconnect in between because of internet connectivity at your place and if you come out from Mettl by the system itself then wait for the connection and then again log into the system using the link. The link will become inactive for those who didn't join even for a single time. It will remain active for those who join on time and available because of any kind of interruption during the exam time to rejoin.
    Don't be panic. Think patiently and behave. Your time will not go until you successfully login to the system.
    Do the necessary uploading on time. 

All the best
Course Instructors

Subject: Competitive examinations question paper-Reg
From: "P. Srinivasan" <psrinivasan@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 13-04-2021, 11:09
To: Kanishk Chaudhary <f20180481@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, HRITIK GUPTA <f20180307@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, KAUSTUV LAHIRI <f20180546@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, MODI ATHARVA SOMSHEKHAR <f20180555@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
BCC: f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in

Dear Students,
Today from 4 to 4 10 lab quiz on Emissivity will be conducted followed by Heat Exchanger experiment.
We have almost come to the end of the semester and there will not be any evaluative component for this course will be held after 20/04/2021 to enable you to prepare for the examination. There will be a Tutorial test VIII 20/04/2021 after your lab class. for one hour. However, it is optional for the students. Anyone can opt out if they have done well in all the 7 tutorials conducted so far as only the best 6 out of 8 will be considered for grading.
We will share the consolidated questions from Heat Transfer part from IES examinations of the last three years from all the portions and will give you one week time to solve on your own interest. After one week, the solutions will be discussed just to make you understand the approach to solve the problem.
This will also be a revision of the course. I may suggest you to take part in this activity.
I hope you enjoy learning heat transfer with all practical applications.
best wishes
P Srinivasan

Dear all,

Hope you are staying safe.

We have compiled an exhaustive list of all Heat Transfer related questions which were asked in GATE and IES (UPSE ESE) in the past three to four years. I am attaching the Word file as well as the PDF file for your convenience.

The final answers are also given at the end of each section if you wish to validate your answers. This can serve as a good revision for the Compre Exam and also if you're interested in attempting GATE / IES in the near future.

Recheck Done, Further Instructions, and Tutorial Class
by Rahul Arora . - Monday, 26 April 2021, 4:47 PM
  	

Dear Students,

Recheck is done and soon you all will receive a report from Mettl on updated status. Question 2(B) is considered for partial marks and is considered for all those who have used the mid-point formula correctlly for both price, quantity, and correct explanation of TR (also checked for those who have not applied for recheck for that question). This is on the basis that at least you know the formula and its application. In case of any further query (not new one) on your recheck request related to part B, kindly contact to Dr. Rajan and he will do the needful but only within 24 hours.  

Don't send any new recheck requests. Those will not be entertained. Those who have submitted their answers on email, their recheck updates will be received in a separate email shortly after this email.

Related to tomorrow's tutorial, there will no tutorial tomorrow instead the practice questions will be taken up by Dr. Krishna in the regular class on Wednesday.  

All the best

Rahul Arora

From: "P. Srinivasan" <psrinivasan@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>

To: "P. Srinivasan" <psrinivasan@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>

Dear Students,
We have completed one semester and the course on Heat Transfer. This courses is offered in II year for the first time. I hope you had a wonderful learning experience and enjoyed the sessions. Tomorrow will be the last lecture of this course for the semester and we will very briefly talk about the different research opportunities and how can pursue your career path in this field if you are interested.
We will have a brief interaction about the courses, coverage and much more importantly your feedback to further improve the teaching and learning process.
I also may plan to offer a course on Power Plant Engineering as an elective, I would like to know the number of students who may be interested in this elective.
I enjoyed teaching this course as we had fruitful discussions and interactions during the session to enhance the learning experience.Some of the session went 45 minutes beyond the class hours. I enjoyed those discussions.
Looking forward to meet you tomorrow.
No PPTs or lecture tomorrow, it will be only discussion.
Please feel free to reach out to me for any doubts/clarification related to the course or any other matter like PS1 if I can resolve/ suggest.
Portion for the comprehensive examination will be all the portion covered after conduction. (Please note, you may need to remember some of the concepts of conduction also to attend the examination.)
All the best.
Stay safe and take care.
We have not met in person. I am sure we will meet sometime in person when you come back to the campus and could recognise your faces. I hope these days will come sooner than later.
Best wishes
P Srinivasan

Picture of Amit Rajnarayan Singh . 	
Eligibility for the 'Clear' Grade
by Amit Rajnarayan Singh . - Friday, 7 May 2021, 8:53 PM
  	Dear all
The pandemic has wreaked havoc all over the world and the situation is dire in our country at the moment. The whole semester has been fraught with challenges on the physical, psychological, and social levels for the students as well as the faculty. These are unprecedented times especially in your young lives and there is a need for unprecedented measures on various fronts.

I have received several emails regarding the course total and I am sorry that I could not reply to many of them because since yesterday Professor Dasgupta, our Head of the Department, and I have been trying out different ways to maximize the number of students whom we can help to become eligible for the 'Clear' grade that has been recently introduced. Since the class average is low, it was not an easy task. After several iterations, considerations, and going back and forth we have decided the following is the best we can do, given the unusual circumstances:

    We have introduced a "Grace Marks Tutorial" component in which the entire class has been given 10 out of 10 marks. Including this component, now we have a total of 5 tutorials.
    We will consider the best 3 out of these 5 tutorials towards your course total.
    The course Gradebook on Nalanda has already been updated to reflect the above changes.
    Every student whose course total is more than 24 is eligible for applying for the "Clear" grade option on the ERP. (Around 97% of the class is now eligible.)

CAVEAT (Please note this very carefully):

    We are fully aware that some students will opt for writing the comprehensive exam or the make-up exam.
    The grace marks may be a disadvantage for some of these students, in terms of relative grading.
    To address this concern, it has been decided that when we will calculate the "non-clear" grades after the comprehensive exam, THE GRACE MARKS TUTORIAL COMPONENT WILL BE REMOVED i.e. the extra marks that have been provided above (ONLY to make the maximum number of students eligible for the "Clear" grade) will NOT be considered towards the course total.
    What does this mean for you? You should not overestimate your standing or performance in the course based on the grace marks. It is exclusively meant to enable those who want to opt-out of the final exam to use the "Clear" grade option.
    For the final "non-clear" grades, we will follow the marking scheme mentioned in the hand-out i.e. we will take the best 3 out of the 4 evaluative tutorials that were actually conducted.
    I understand that you will have further questions about how marks of the students who will opt-out using the "clear" grade will be accounted for in the final grading. The AUGSD and the head of the departments have already thought about this issue and have come up with ways to ensure that those who choose to write the exam are not at a loss. Those details will be made available later.

Wish you all the best!

- Dr. Amit R. Singh

Picture of Rahul Arora . 	
Instruction for the Tomorrow's (21st May 2021) Comprehensive Exam Scheduled at 3 PM
by Rahul Arora . - Thursday, 20 May 2021, 3:27 PM
  	

Dear Students,

Following are the final instructions for the comprehensive exam scheduled tomorrow (21 May 2021) at 3 PM: [those who are going to appear tomorrow]

    Questions are divided into three sections: Section A, Section B, Section C
    All questions are compulsory
    Part A contains MCQs with No Negative Marking
    Part B contains descriptive/numerical-type questions from the part taught by Dr. Rahul
    Part C contains descriptive/numerical-type questions from the part taught by Dr. Krishna
    Navigation between sections is allowed
    Calculator is allowed
    For Part B and Part C, you need to write your answers in the space provided. You need Not upload your answers separately and no uploading is allowed and available. Please write the main answer in a new line and try to highlight it. We asked questions in such a way that you can manage typing. Also do not forget to explain/interpret your answer. In economics, without interpretation, a number does not have meaning.
    The exam would be of 120 minutes in total. Make sure that in the 120th minute you click the submit/OK button and finish your test.
    In case of any disconnection in between and time wasted because of reconnecting, extra 15 minutes (15 Maximum or the actual time if it is lesser) will be given at the end to compensate for that time loss. No more time would be given in any case. The link will be shared at 8:45 AM and the exam can be started around 8:55 AM. 
    Mettl note down your screen activities, your activities, and activities/gadgets present in your room. So please be aware of it and be honest while giving your exam.
    The exam is open book in the sense that you can refer to the slides, e-copy of the textbook during the exam, and other lecture material shared over NALANDA. Any extra material over the internet opened or seen during the exam will be eligible for a penalty in terms of marks. Remember we are looking at your screen activities also.

The syllabus you all knew. The concepts taught post-mid-sem. From the game theory, you can leave the Max-min rule because that requires one class. After the exam, for your information, I would share the two-page notes on this for your learning only.

All the best
Rahul Arora (IC)

Subject: Project proposal for ISRO-Reg,
From: "P. Srinivasan" <psrinivasan@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 16-06-2021, 21:50
To: Chennu Ranganayakulu <c.ranganayakulu@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
BCC: f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in

Dear Students,
It is nice to connect with you again for an important cause.
ISRO would like to develop technology in certain areas by funding the project as per the attachment. It needs a PI, Co PI and a few interested & motivated students to work on the project for two years. We would like to submit a proposal in the area of Heat Exchanger as per the project number 369 in the attachment.
This mail is to get the willingness of 3-4 students to work on the project if they are interested. I am sure some of you will be keen to work on this project. We have already submitted another proposal on Heat Pipe design in which 4 of your classmates are members of the project.
We hope to get both the projects to work on if sanctioned. You may recall Prof. Chennu has written a book on compact heat exchanger.
If more students express interest, the selection will be made based on the following criteria.
1) CGPA
2) Mark scored in Heat Transfer (PCT) if the student has opted for cleared grade and total marks if they have written the comprehensive examinations. 
3) Interaction with the students
4) Willingness to develop new product and new business venture.
Interested students may mail me directly with the details given above along with a brief resume.
Last date for submission of the proposal is 20 July 2021. Send your details by tomorrow  5PM.
Best wishes
P Srinivasan

First lecture class on 24/08/2021
by Saket Verma . - Monday, 23 August 2021, 10:56 AM
  	

Dear Students,

Welcome to the course ENGINES MOTORS AND MOBILITY (ME F317) formerly known as IC Engines (ME F212).

You can find the course handout in the "General' section as well as from the AUGSD webpage.

The first class (on 24/08/2021 - Tuesday - 4-4:50 PM) happens to be a tutorial class. Hence I will take the lecture on this class, and we will have a formal introduction to this course.

I have already shared a google meet link with you for the lecture sessions (Wed & Fri - 12 - 12:50 PM). Please use the same to attend the first lecture. The link is give below as well for convenience. I will create a separate link for upcoming tutorial classes.

See you tomorrow! Best wishes

Lecture: ME F317 - ENGINES MOTORS AND MOBILITY
Wednesday, August 25 · 12:00 – 1:00pm

Subject: ME F314/ MF F314: CANVAS page for Tutorial Tests
From: Gaurav Watts <gaurav.watts@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 23-08-2021, 17:03
CC: "M.S Dasgupta" <dasgupta@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, Amol Marutrao Marathe <amolmm@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, "Jitendra S. Rathore" <jitendrarathore@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, Amit Singh <amit.singh@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
BCC: f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in

Dear Students,

    All the tutorial tests for the course shall be conducted through the course page on CANVAS. 
    An invitation to join the page has already been sent to you. Check your email inbox.
    If you have not received an invitation or if you are facing any issue in joining the course page, share your details by replying to this email.
    You must complete your profile on CANVAS so that your full name appears in the student list. 
    You must join the page before the first tutorial class on Thursday (August 26, 2021).
    Tutorial tests will be posted as assignments on the page.
    You must submit your solutions as a single scanned pdf file before the due time for every tutorial test.
    Email submissions will not be accepted.
    Rechecking requests, if any, shall be submitted by writing a private comment under the marks assigned to you.
    You may also install the CANVAS STUDENT mobile app for students on your mobile device for easy access.


-- 
Regards,
Gaurav Watts,
Assistant Professor,
Department of Mechanical Engineering,

Subject: 11511002405_ME F317_AUG_2021: Next class - 7/09/2021
From: "Saket Verma . (via Nalanda)" <saket.verma@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 05-09-2021, 15:03
To: "ASWIN BENEDICT" <f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Reply-to: "Saket Verma ."

11511002405_ME F317_AUG_2021 » Forums » Announcements » Next class - 7/09/2021
Picture of Saket Verma . 	
Next class - 7/09/2021
by Saket Verma . - Sunday, 5 September 2021, 3:01 PM
  	

Dear Students,

In the next class on Tuesday (7/09/2021), we will be discussing Fuel-air cycle of IC engines. To understand that better it is required that you revise Otto, Diesel and Daul cycles (Air stadard cycles) that you have studied in the previous subjects. You can follow "Chapter-2 Air-Standard Cycles and Their Analysis " of the text book V Ganesan or the same topic from other reference books. Please come prepared.

Best wishes

See this post in context

Subject: Details about Tuesday second hour (MF F316) class
From: Srikanta Routroy <srikanta@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 18-09-2021, 13:23
To: Srikanta Routroy <srikanta@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, Divyansh Patel <divyansh.patel@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, F ABDULLAH SULTAN <p20180033@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, SHAILENDER SINGH <p20180034@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
BCC: f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in

Dear Students

The class for Tuesday second hour will be held at their respective sections.  However, the students registered in T3 and T4 will join in this google meet (meet.google.com/rjt-angi-rew) as Dr. Patel is out of station. The group project progress will be discussed in Tuesday’s class. All the groups will give a small presentation not more than 3 to 4 minutes regarding the progress made in the project. The focus of the presentation should be on work division, material collected, discussion among the group members and another issue. The instructor of each group will give their remarks  after the presentation. 

-- 

With Best Regards

Srikanta Routroy

Tutorial class - 21/09/2021
by Saket Verma . - Monday, 20 September 2021, 7:51 PM
  	

Dear Students,

In tomorrow's tutorial class (21/09/2021), an introduction session is scheduled to understand the basics of SimulationX software. You will learn how to start with and use SimulationX software to model various systems related to vehicular modelling. Please use the below link to join the session:

Tutorial:  Engines, Motors, and Mobility (ME F317)
Tuesday, September 21 · 4:00 – 5:00pm
Google Meet joining info
Video call link: https://meet.google.com/sam-kipt-udt
Or dial: ‪(US) +1 475-444-3532‬ PIN: ‪657 028 121‬#
More phone numbers: https://tel.meet/sam-kipt-udt?pin=2711453695950

Best wishes

11511002433_BITS F451_AUG_2021 » Forums » Announcements » Project Presentation Tomorrow - 25/09/2021
Picture of Avinash Gautam . 	
Project Presentation Tomorrow - 25/09/2021
by Avinash Gautam . - Friday, 24 September 2021, 6:06 PM
  	

Dear Students,

Your project presentation is scheduled for tomorrow. Three groups will be presenting during the class hour. And the remaining groups will present from 3:00 PM to 5:00 PM.

You can check your schedule on the following link

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1kyXbujSk4UrGdgEqOVWPgBKe8Zp28BUjyOP04nlL5sw/edit?usp=sharing

All of you should join us over the following Google meet link. All group members should be present in the meeting. You should join 10 min before your slot time. For example, if your presentation is scheduled at 3:20 PM then you should join the meeting at 3:10 PM.

https://meet.google.com/vqq-zfne-xqa


Best wishes,

Avinash

Subject: Regarding Tutorial Class on Tuesday (12/10/2021)
From: Srikanta Routroy <srikanta@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
Date: 09-10-2021, 12:10
To: Srikanta Routroy <srikanta@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, Divyansh Patel <divyansh.patel@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, F ABDULLAH SULTAN <p20180033@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>, SHAILENDER SINGH <p20180034@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in>
BCC: f20190579@pilani.bits-pilani.ac.in

Dear Students

The solution of Tutorial 3 and Tutorial 4 will be discussed in Tuesday’s tutorial class.

There will also be an interaction regarding the progress of the group project that you are doing in the Manufacturing Management course. We know some of you may be travelling. The members who are not travelling should join the meeting and discuss the progress and difficulties (if any). However, if all or most of the members in a group are travelling, they may ask for some other time for interaction with their respective tutorial instructor.

It is non-evaluative. 

With Best Regards

Srikanta Routroy

Class schedule post mid-sem
by Saket Verma . - Monday, 8 November 2021, 9:27 PM
  	

Dear Student,

We have received the information that post mid-sem the classes will be in off-line mode with the following schedule:

Lec/Tut 	Instructor 	Class room 	Day and time
L1  	SAKET VERMA  	5106 	W F 5 
T1  	Saket Verma  	1202 	T 9
T2  	Anish Kumar(RS)  	1232 	T 9
T3  	T Lachana Dora(RS)  	1226 	T 9
T4  	Diplesh Gautam(RS)  	1231 	T  9

The lecture rooms has impartus facility. For the time being we will also continue with parallel google meet sessions for off-campus students.

Please note that the next tutorial class on 09/11/2021 stand cancelled. We will meet on 10/11/2021 in the lecture class as per the above schedule.

See you! Best regards
